John Edward: language skills are a key skill for a global citizen
The learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test scores. The success has been enhanced by individual and communal success in sports, arts, music and other community-based projects.
These schools, with more than 30,000 students across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), aim to provide a high level of service to their students as well as the parents of their pupils.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for careers of their choice, graduate and higher education, and global citizenship.
As an actor in the field of education who can design and implement customized study content, we have noticed the position of languages as a popular and desirable subject to continue in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message goes to his or her heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships with people in other countries.
From this year's latest test results, we find that languages are at the top of the list in terms of pass rate among private schools.
68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data were collected from 74 schools belonging to the SCIS, and it was found that among the students who received the highest grade of A, 72 per cent studied Mandarin, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French, and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are held in the same esteem as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school study program and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment Office in 2014 found that 17 percent of situations in which an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary for the promotion of young people's future career development.
The more potential work tasks require language skills, the more essential these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied a second language, he or she will have an advantage over this lifelong skill in the future, regardless of which career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner puts a person with language skills automatically ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey conducted by YouGov, 75 percent of the more than 4,000 British adults are unable to have a conversation in a foreign language, and French was the only language to have a two-digit number of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
Especially the knowledge of languages in developing countries gives children a better opportunity to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while others specifically teach languages that are expected to be important to British people in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Despite your child's interests, there are always several language options in private schools, taught by specialized teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment,languages will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be seen as "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high-level Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council for Private Schools SCIS
