Harvard students complete an adequate rest instructional course
All undergraduate students at Harvard University are attending a course this year designed to increase students' rest. The course is a counter-attack to the thriving macho culture at the university, where students press long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of the basics of their own well-being.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes the course will be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, in my senior year of study?'
No one had ever told him about the need for a dream, which I found surprising," he told the Telegraph in an interview.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard University's Faculty of Medicine and deputy director of health services at the university, says the university ended up organizing a course after they had heard how students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week of study.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with an image of a dormitory room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, and thus get information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effect of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behavior.
However, we believe that they have a right to know about these things in exactly the same way that they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking," adds Professor Czeisler.
All-night study marathons are still a matter of pride, according to Professor Czeisler, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting adequate and quality sleep should be the students' 'secret weapon' against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a brain-like state, which is why a person is constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus for a course covering all students on campus.
He hopes that all graduate students could complete a similar course of study before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime as well as waking up in the morning, as well as telling them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electric displays and LED lighting "blue light" on circadian rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
