Environmental organization eavesdrops on bats' hidden lives
A new study in the Scottish Highlands aims to find out how bats use the terrain to hunt for food.
The new research is hoped to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and to guide future conservation efforts.
A study conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland is looking at pestle and dwarf bats, as well as earworts and waterfowl in the Inverewe Garden area of the Botanical Garden in Wester Ross.
In the study, special storage devices are placed at important points in the area to monitor the activity of bats during the season.
The organization's employees and volunteers also perform mobile measurements using portable observation devices.
The frequencies of the pronunciations, as well as the species in question, are ensured by expert analysis.
Based on the results, a habitat map and report are created in which the behaviour of the bats can be shown in an image that follows the scale of the area.
Rob Dewar, the organization's conservation advisor, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats, and how they are exploited by different species.
The information helps with the planning of habitat areas, such as the creation of meadows and the management of forest areas, so that bats and related species are taken into account.
The bat populations of Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined considerably in the last 100 years.
Construction and earthworks threaten the resting places and habitats of bats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flypapers and certain chemicals used in building materials, as well as attacks by pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to night hunting habits, their ears are more useful for catching prey than their eyes.
Bats use advanced echolocation technology to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The National Trust for Scotland is an organization dedicated to the protection of the rural environment that maintains more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country — and they take bats seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly conduct surveys, rest-place inspections and, in some cases, animal rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only protected area dedicated to the protection of bats on the land of Threave Manor in the Dumfries and Galloway region, where eight of Scotland's ten species of bats are found.
According to groundskeeper David Thompson, the area is ideal for bats.
"Threave suits bats very well," he says.
"We have old buildings and trees and overall a good living environment.
Not everything is known about the bats yet, so our work here and in other areas of the organization will help us better understand what the bats need to succeed."
He stresses the importance of inspecting buildings for bats before undertaking restoration work, as the destruction of one of the bats' resting places can inadvertently cause the death of up to 400 female bats and chicks and obliterate an entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and killing, disturbing or destroying their resting places is prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official of the Bats Protection Association, encourages the public to participate in the conservation work.
He says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we still don't know how their populations are doing."
